04536nam a22006495i 9781477308592DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015023704  a97814773085927 a10.7560/7266112doi  a(DE-B1597)588762  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aNC1875.U6bT456 2015 4aF1386.4.T597S74 2016 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a972/.5308311 aMeikle, Jeffrey L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPostcard America :bCurt Teich and the Imaging of a Nation, 1931-1950 /cJeffrey L. Meikle. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. “They Do Say It’s Real”: An Introduction to Linen Postcards -- t2. Curt Teich and the Early History of Postcards -- t3. The Linen Postcard: Innovation and Aesthetics -- t4. Landscapes in Linen Postcards: A National Imaginary -- tPortfolio 1: Landscapes -- tRepresentative Vistas -- tThe Southwest: A Regional Aesthetic -- tTravel and Tourism -- tScenic People -- tResources -- tInfrastructure and Transportation -- t5. Cityscapes in Linen Postcards: Images of Modernity -- tPortfolio 11: Cityscapes -- tOverviews -- tSkyscrapers -- tMain Streets -- tLandmarks -- tRecreation -- tWorld’s Fairs -- tAccommodations -- t6. From a Rearview Mirror: Contemporary Reflections -- tNotes -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the Great Depression through the early postwar years, any postcard sent in America was more than likely a “linen” card. Colorized in vivid, often exaggerated hues and printed on card stock embossed with a linen-like texture, linen postcards celebrated the American scene with views of majestic landscapes, modern cityscapes, roadside attractions, and other notable features. These colorful images portrayed the United States as shimmering with promise, quite unlike the black-and-white worlds of documentary photography or Life magazine. Linen postcards were enormously popular, with close to a billion printed and sold. Postcard America offers the first comprehensive study of these cards and their cultural significance. Drawing on the production files of Curt Teich & Co. of Chicago, the originator of linen postcards, Jeffrey L. Meikle reveals how photographic views were transformed into colorized postcard images, often by means of manipulation—adding and deleting details or collaging bits and pieces from several photos. He presents two extensive portfolios of postcards—landscapes and cityscapes—that comprise a representative iconography of linen postcard views. For each image, Meikle explains the postcard’s subject, describes aspects of its production, and places it in social and cultural contexts. In the concluding chapter, he shifts from historical interpretation to a contemporary viewpoint, considering nostalgia as a motive for collectors and others who are fascinated today by these striking images.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aPostcardsxCollectors and collectingzUnited States. 0aPostcardszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72661140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477308592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477308592/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK